This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of computational linguistics (cs.CL) as it discusses syntactic theory and its formalization. The paper also mentions the treatment of long-distance dependencies, which is a common topic in natural language processing. 

The paper may also belong to the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG) as it proposes a new approach to syntactic structure that involves topological operations. 

The sub-category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) is also a possibility as the paper discusses the manipulation of elements to yield derived, complex elements, which is a common topic in AI research. 

The sub-category of software development (cs.SD) is a possibility as the paper proposes a new way of conceptualizing syntax, which could potentially lead to the development of new software tools for natural language processing. 

Finally, the sub-category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) is a possibility as the paper discusses the combinatorial operations involved in syntactic structure, which is related to the study of algorithms and data structures.
